Insights:¶

I choose to discard 'poutcome' from the analysis as most of the outcomes are unknown and thus do not contribute much to the dataset overall. The 'contact' column will also be discarded based on the countplot distribution. The people who subscribed were mostly contacted through cell-phone, however this is not insightful as most people were contacted through this cell-phone. 'day' will also be excluded from the analysis as the countplots show somewhat of a uniform distribution for subscribed and non-subscribed individuals.

#Splitting into train/test datasets
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
X = final_df.drop('Target',axis=1)  
Y = final_df['Target']
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, Y, test_size=0.3, random_state=1)

Logistic Regression and Decision Tree Models¶

Logistic Regression¶

In [24]:
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
#Fitting model on training data
logreg_model = LogisticRegression(solver="liblinear")
logreg_model.fit(X_train, y_train)
#Predicting
predictions = logreg_model.predict(X_test)
In [25]:
test_score = logreg_model.score(X_test, y_test)
train_score = logreg_model.score(X_train, y_train)
recall = recall_score(y_test, predictions)
precision = precision_score(y_test, predictions)
f1 = f1_score(y_test, predictions)
roc = roc_auc_score(y_test, predictions)
In [26]:
#There were 260 false positives and 1000 false negatives for the logistic regression model
from sklearn import metrics
conf = metrics.confusion_matrix(y_test, predictions, labels=[1, 0])
df_cm = pd.DataFrame(conf, index = [i for i in ["Observed Yes"," Observed No"]],
                  columns = [i for i in ["Predicted Yes","Predicted No"]])
plt.figure(figsize = (7,5))
sns.heatmap(df_cm, annot=True)
Out[26]:
<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x7faec7b84610>
In [27]:
#Overall, this is a decent model as it has 89.8% test accuracy
#The F1 score is very low however due to low precision and recall values. This model is able to predict
    #when an individual will not subscribe well, however is not as good with predicting who will subscribe
results = pd.DataFrame({'Method':['Logistic Regression'], 'Train Accuracy': [train_score], 
                    'Test Accuracy': [test_score], 'Recall': [recall], 
                     'Precision': [precision], 'F1 Score': [f1], 'ROC Auc Score': [roc]})
results = results[['Method', 'Train Accuracy', 'Test Accuracy', 'Recall', 'Precision',
                    'F1 Score', 'ROC Auc Score']]
results

Conclusion¶

If false positives are highly prevalent from the model outputs, this means that we would often predict that an individual will subscribe but in actuality they do not, costing the bank more money. On the other hand, if false negatives are more prevalent from the model outputs, then this means that we would predict more individuals to not subscribe although they do subscribe. For the bank to take a less risky approach, they would want to minimize the false positive rate as these would become more costly for them. Thus, precision would be a key metric for analysis of each model. However, we should also take into account recall as too many false negatives would give inaccurate understanding of subscribers. Thus, the three main metrics we consider by priority are precision, followed by recall, followed by the F1 score, which is the weighted average of recall and precision.

From the final results table, one can clearly see that the ensemble methods and the other ones have very similar test accuracy. We note that the bagging model has the greatest recall amongst all of the models, meaning that it was able to correctly predict which individuals subscribed to a term deposit. Random forest, on the other hand, has the highest precision, meaning that it predicted the number of true subscribers most accurately. The F1 score was the highest in the bagging model. Due to bagging having a significantly greater recall and F1 score while only being slightly worse in precision than the random forest model, I say that bagging is the best model for this problem. Additionally, the ROC AUC score of the bagging model is the best out of all models, meaning it is able to distinguish between non-subscribers and subscribers the most accurately.
